# ============================================================================
# greenfield-app.loop — build a whole app from NOTHING, A to Z, as one flow
# ============================================================================
#
# THE BIG PICTURE
#   A `flow` chains whole .loop files end to end, passing each step's result
#   forward as context for the next. This flow is the complete greenfield
#   lifecycle — idea → backlog → architecture → a working app:
#
#       discover  ──▶  design  ──▶  for each story ──▶  story-template
#       (interview)    (blueprint)   (build the backlog, one story at a time)
#
#   1. discover.loop  — interviews you in chat and writes sprint.yaml (the backlog).
#   2. design.loop    — turns sprint.yaml into design.md (the architecture note),
#                       and a human approves it before the build starts.
#   3. for each story — runs story-template.loop ONCE PER STORY in sprint.yaml.
#                       Each story's text (epic + title + acceptance) arrives as
#                       that run's context, so the same checklist builds every
#                       story without you naming them here.
#
# WHY A FLOW AND NOT ONE GIANT LOOP
#   Each phase has a different shape of "done": discovery is done when the
#   backlog file exists, design when a human approves the note, a story when its
#   tests pass. A flow lets each phase use its own verification and its own human
#   gates, while the chain wires them together. The chain is FAIL-FAST: if
#   discover never produces a sprint.yaml, design never runs.
#
# THE BACKLOG IS THE HINGE
#   discover WRITES sprint.yaml; `for each` READS it. So the number of stories
#   built, and what each one is, is decided live during the interview — not
#   hard-coded here. Re-run discovery, get a different app. This file never
#   changes.
#
# DEPENDENCY (do not author here)
#   story-template.loop is provided by a SEPARATE template in this same
#   templates/ directory — the per-story checklist (implement → security →
#   manual QA, with its own done-when, reflect, thrash guard, and gates). This
#   flow only references it.
#
# RUN IT
#   /loopflow run greenfield-app.loop     # in the Claude Code conversation
#   loop run greenfield-app.loop          # headless via the CLI
#   (Run `show` first to eyeball the shape before you run anything for real.)
#
# GIT SAFETY
#   No git: block here, so the built-in safe default applies to the loops this
#   flow runs: work on a branch, commit when the goal is met, never push to
#   main/master. Add a file-level git: block (e.g. open a pull request) only
#   once you trust the flow end to end.

# TODO: rename the flow to your app (this label is just for humans + the viz).
flow "greenfield app: my new app":

  # STEP 1 — DISCOVER. Interview the user in chat; write sprint.yaml.
  #   Done when the backlog file exists (the artifact check, not the chat).
  run "discover.loop"

  # STEP 2 — DESIGN. Receives discover's result as context. Turn sprint.yaml
  #   into design.md; a human approves the architecture before we build.
  then run "design.loop"

  # STEP 3 — BUILD. Iterate the backlog: run the story checklist once per story
  #   in sprint.yaml. The current story's text becomes that run's context (what
  #   to build); the checks inside story-template.loop are the SAME every time.
  #   A failed story pauses the flow and asks whether to continue or stop.
  then for each story in "sprint.yaml":
    run "story-template.loop"
